\end_layout

\end_inset

j Ak . 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
eeq
\end_layout

\end_inset

 I.e., the magnetic field is simply the curl of the vector potential 
\begin_inset Formula $A_k$
\end_inset

. Notice that the magnetic field is unperturbed if we add a term 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_k (\sqrt{\gamma} \Phi)$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $A_k$
\end_inset

, since the curl of a gradient is zero. Thus we have the freedom to add such a term to the vector potential. This is called our 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

gauge
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 freedom, and although our choice of 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sqrt{\gamma} \Phi)$
\end_inset

 does not matter in unigrid simulations, truncation errors from interpolations of 
\begin_inset Formula $A_k$
\end_inset

 on AMR refinement boundaries will convert purely gauge modes into a combination of gauge 
\shape italic
and physical
\family default
\series default
\shape default
 modes. If the gauge modes do not propagate, repeated interpolations common on these refinement boundaries will lead to a build-up of errors, crashing simulations. So we choose to evolve 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sqrt{\gamma} \Phi)$
\end_inset

 forward in time via the Lorenz gauge condition (Eq.
\begin_inset space ~

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:EMGauge"

\end_inset

), in which all gauge modes may propagate, effectively disallowing the build-up of errors on AMR refinement boundaries. We add an additional damping term to the standard Lorenz gauge condition, so that modes of 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sqrt{\gamma}
\Phi)$
\end_inset

 damp to zero as 
\begin_inset Formula $r\to\infty$
\end_inset

. This reduces the buildup of errors on the outer boundary, caused by approximate outer boundary conditions.
\end_layout

