\begin_layout Subsubsection
Fill basic data structures and initialize GRMHD RHS variables
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First you will see that we set a struct called 
\family typewriter
eos
\family default
\series default
\shape default
, short for Equation Of State. This is an easily extensible data structure that stores all the required information for the equation of state, which closes the set of GRMHD equations. We must store the parameters that populate this struct as separate variables in 
\family typewriter
param.ccl
\family default
\series default
\shape default
 and 
\family typewriter
interface.ccl
\family default
\series default
\shape default
, since, to my knowledge, ET does not support defining 
\family typewriter
struct
\family default
\series default
\shape default
's in these files. (FIXME).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next you will notice that we declare 
\family typewriter
in_prims
\family default
\series default
\shape default
, 
\family typewriter
out_prims_r
\family default
\series default
\shape default
, 
\family typewriter
out_prims_l
\family default
\series default
\shape default
, which are arrays of the 
\family typewriter
gf_and_gz_struct
\family default
\series default
\shape default
 type of 
\family typewriter
struct
\family default
\series default
\shape default
. 
\family typewriter
gf_and_gz_struct
\family default
\series default
\shape default
 is very simply defined as 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Verbatim
struct gf_and_gz_struct {
\end_layout

\begin_layout Verbatim
  double *gf;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Verbatim
  int gz_lo[4],gz_hi[4];
\end_layout

\begin_layout Verbatim
}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is a structure that simply points to the address in memory of the gridfunction, and stores the ghostzone information for that gridfunction. Ghostzone information comes in very handy when we need to reconstruct twice, as is the case when evaluating the induction equation on staggered grids.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
FIXME: Next we set the gridfunction 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi=e^{\phi}$
\end_inset

. Really this should be done by the BSSN thorn (i.e., the thorn that handles the metric evolution).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We then set a couple of arrays of pointers, that simply point to the address in memory of metric-related and 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

 gridfunctions. Technically we do not need to store 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

 in memory, since it can be recomputed. However, the computational cost is not very low, and this code assumes, to an extent, that memory space is cheap. For cases in which you are running too low on memory, you may want to rewrite this code to remove 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

. There are several other optimizations you could make that reduce the memory cost at the price of more memory accesses and higher CPU cost.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, we set the RHSs of all conservative variables to zero.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection

\family typewriter
compute_tau_rhs_curvature_terms_and_TUPmunu
\family default
\series default
\shape default

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Eq.
\begin_inset space ~

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tau_curvature"

\end_inset

 contains the only term on the RHS of the GRMHD equations that depends only on 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

 and metric quantities without derivatives. Now, 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

 will come in handy a bit later when we actually need to compute the metric source terms for 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{S}_i$
\end_inset

, and the rest of Eq.
\begin_inset space ~

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tau_curvature"

\end_inset

 which depend on derivatives of the metric.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection

\family typewriter
ftilde_gf_compute
\family default
\series default
\shape default

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next we specify the first flux direction (
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

=1), and then compute the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{f}$
\end_inset

 used in the Piecewise Parabolic Method (PPM). This function is used for flattening face values around shocks.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection

\family typewriter
reconstruct_set_of_prims_PPM
\family default
\series default
\shape default

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is the master function for applying PPM reconstruction to a set of variables. All hydro primitive variables (
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_b,P,v^i$
\end_inset

) are defined at grid vertices, yet in the GRMHD evolution equations, we must compute fluxes of these quantities. Evaluating these fluxes requires that divergences be computed–a task ideally suited for a simple finite difference approach, or so one might think. In reality, when characteristics cross and the resulting shocks develop into discontinuities, simple finite differences across shocks results in the Gibbs phenomenon, in which approximating these derivatives with simple, overlapping polynomials results in wild oscillations around physical discontinuities. We get around this problem via a more sophisticated algorithm, as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First, we very carefully computing the flux in the 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

-direction by 
\shape italic
reconstructing
\family default
\series default
\shape default
 primitive variables, which are defined at 
\begin_inset Formula $(i,j,k)$
\end_inset

, to the cell 
\shape italic
face
\family default
\series default
\shape default
 at 
\begin_inset Formula $(i+\frac{1}{2},j,k)$
\end_inset

. We employ the standard PPM reconstruction scheme of Collela and Woodward in this code, modified so that it depends on only 3 ghostzones (the 4-ghostzone version includes better shock detection). This scheme, which is third-order accurate in resolution for smooth flows and first-order for shocks, effectively reduces spurious oscillations from developing across shocks.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection

\family typewriter
add_fluxes_and_source_terms_to_hydro_rhss
\family default
\series default
\shape default

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After reconstructing all the GRMHD primitive variables in a single direction, we are then ready to evaluate the flux terms on the RHSs of the GR HYDRO equations. Before doing that, this routine starts by evaluating the remaining source terms for 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{S}_i$
\end_inset

, then it calls the function that computes the flux terms, called 
\family typewriter
mhdflux
\family default
\series default
\shape default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
mhdflux()
\family default
\series default
\shape default
 (located in 
\family typewriter
src/mhdflux.C
\family default
\series default
\shape default
 takes the reconstructed GRMHD primitive variables and uses them to evaluate the flux terms on the RHSs of the GR HYDRO equations. It starts by evaluating the enthalpy 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 and the internal energy 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

 based on the equation of state. Then it computes fluxes and approximate characteristic speeds for all the conservative quantities. Note that these speeds overestimate the actual characteristic speeds, which results in a more dissipative (but potentially more stable) algorithm. Contributing further to the dissipation, we compute fluxes at face values via the original HLL scheme, which is known to be overly dissipative. There are better schemes, such as HLLC or HLLD (Athena code uses) (FIXME), but the goal of this thorn release is that it yield results that are to roundoff precision identical to those obtained from the original GRMHD code of the Illinois NR group.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After 
\family typewriter
mhdflux()
\family default
\series default
\shape default
 is called, we then compute the GR HYDRO RHS quantities via simple finite differences, so that, in the case of the 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

-direction, the RHS flux term is simply 
\begin_inset Formula $(F_{i+1/2,j,k} -
F_{i-1/2,j,k})/dx$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Evaluation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_*,\tilde{S}_i,$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 RHS's in the 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

-directions follows trivially from how it is done in the 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

-direction. However, evaluating the RHSs of the induction equations, while straightforward, requires quite a bit more bookkeeping, which is described in the next section.
\end_layout

