\begin_inset Formula $B^x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B^y$
\end_inset

 so that they are defined at staggered points (
\begin_inset Formula $i+1/2,j+1/2,k$
\end_inset

). To do this, we first note that the gridfunction 
\family typewriter
Bx_stagger
\family default
\series default
\shape default
 is defined at (
\begin_inset Formula $i+1/2,j,k$
\end_inset

) and 
\family typewriter
Bz_stagger
\family default
\series default
\shape default
 at (
\begin_inset Formula $i,j,k+1/2$
\end_inset

) (similarly, 
\family typewriter
By_stagger
\family default
\series default
\shape default
 is defined at (
\begin_inset Formula $i,j+1/2,k$
\end_inset

). 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
So to get 
\family typewriter
Bx_stagger
\family default
\series default
\shape default
 at the needed (
\begin_inset Formula $i+1/2,j+1/2,k$
\end_inset

), we reconstruct it along the 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

-direction to (
\begin_inset Formula $i+1/2,j-1/2,k$
\end_inset

) and use a simple 
\begin_inset Formula $j\to j+1$
\end_inset

 shift.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Similarly, to get 
\family typewriter
By_stagger
\family default
\series default
\shape default
 at the needed (
\begin_inset Formula $i+1/2,j+1/2,k$
\end_inset

), we reconstruct it along the 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

-direction to (
\begin_inset Formula $i-1/2,j+1/2,k$
\end_inset

) and use a simple 
\begin_inset Formula $i\to i+1$
\end_inset

 shift. 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Finally, 
\begin_inset Formula $v^y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v^z$
\end_inset

 are defined at (
\begin_inset Formula $i,j,k$
\end_inset

). So to get them to the needed (
\begin_inset Formula $i+1/2,j+1/2,k$
\end_inset

), we reconstruct first along 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 to (
\begin_inset Formula $i-1/2,j,k$
\end_inset

) and then along 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

, which gets us to (
\begin_inset Formula $i-1/2,j-1/2,k$
\end_inset

). Then we use a simple 
\begin_inset Formula $i\to i+1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j\to j+1$
\end_inset

 shift, which brings us to (
\begin_inset Formula $i+1/2,j+1/2,k$
\end_inset

). 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we simply followed these steps for computing 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{ijk} v^j B^k$
\end_inset

 in sequence of 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, 
\family typewriter
driver_evaluate_MHD_rhs.C
\family default
\series default
\shape default
) would certainly be much easier to read. However, this would also result in a less efficient code, that either uses more memory or makes more than the minimum number of calls to the reconstruction routines (pick your poison). To remedy this, I decided to comment the 
\family typewriter
driver_evaluate_MHD_rhs()
\family default
\series default
\shape default
) function extensively, adding many bookkeeping notes.
\end_layout

